04562nam a22008415i 9780231527200DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315272007 a10.7312/noud153942doi  a(DE-B1597)459174  a(OCoLC)794494009  a(OCoLC)979739703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aQK46b.M36 2015 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a5802231 aNoudelmann, François, eauthor.14aThe Philosopher's Touch :bSartre, Nietzsche, and Barthes at the Piano /cFrançois Noudelmann. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEuropean Perspectives: A Series in Social Thought and Cultural Criticism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Intuition -- t2. The Off -Beat Piano -- t3. Why I Am a Great Pianist -- t4. The Piano Touches Me -- t5. Resonances -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRenowned philosopher and prominent French critic François Noudelmann engages the musicality of Jean-Paul Sartre, Friedrich Nietzsche, and Roland Barthes, all of whom were amateur piano players and acute lovers of the medium. Though piano playing was a crucial art for these thinkers, their musings on the subject are largely scant, implicit, or discordant with each philosopher's oeuvre. Noudelmann both recovers and integrates these perspectives, showing that the manner in which these philosophers played, the composers they adored, and the music they chose reveals uncommon insight into their thinking styles and patterns.Noudelmann positions the physical and theoretical practice of music as a dimension underpinning and resonating with Sartre's, Nietzsche's, and Barthes's unique philosophical outlook. By reading their thought against their music, he introduces new critical formulations and reorients their trajectories, adding invaluable richness to these philosophers' lived and embodied experiences. The result heightens the multiple registers of being and the relationship between philosophy and the senses that informed so much of their work. A careful reader of music, Noudelmann maintains an elegant command of the texts under his gaze and appreciates the discursive points of musical and philosophical scholarship they involve, especially with regard to recent research and cutting-edge critique.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aBotanyxHistory. 0aBotanyxPhilosophy. 0aHuman-plant relationships. 0aMusic and philosophy. 0aPlantsxAdaptation. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh1 aReilly, Brian.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/noud15394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231527200.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG